# pr-rebase-conflict-resolution-patterns — History

## v1.15.0 (2026-07-12)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus PR #2056 rebase (branch `2054-auto-impl`, "[Critical] Fail closed autonomous auto-merge paths"; 17 commits, 65 files, rebased forward ~38 commits onto `origin/main`)

**Verification:** verified-local — the four new findings below (§§ Q, R, and the extensions to §§ L and C) are backed by local investigation during the actual rebase session: each fix was applied and the specific check re-run and observed to pass (ruff C901 dropped below threshold after extraction, the specific pytest test passed after the assertion fix, the doc's jq assertion made consistent with the prose, the workflow-inventory pre-commit hook passed after the stale row was removed). These were NOT yet confirmed against this skill PR's own CI gate at authoring time. The skill remains verified-ci overall (prior material, hundreds of PRs across the ecosystem).

### What changed
- Added triggers #22-25 to `## When to Use`, covering: a complexity-gate regression from combining two clean rebase-side changes; a stale test assertion surviving in a byte-identical (never-conflicted) test file because an unrelated commit changed a shared contract; a doc/policy conflict that is really a whole-file chronology question, not independent per-hunk edits; and a deleted file leaving a stale row in a companion inventory/index table.
- Wove a new META-LESSON into `#### C2. Post-rebase verification checklist`: zero conflict markers plus individually-correct hunks are NOT sufficient evidence of a correct rebase for a large multi-commit rebase — run the full pre-commit suite tree-wide, the actual test suite end-to-end, and check whole-file chronology on any conflicted doc/policy file.
- Added `#### Q. Silent auto-merge introduces new complexity violations` — a THIRD flavor of clean-auto-merge-hides-a-defect (distinct from § L test-mock divergence and § K cross-PR semantic collision): combining two independently-clean changes from the two sides of ONE rebase pushed `hephaestus/automation/pipeline/stages/implementation.py`'s `_gate` method from McCabe complexity 12 to `C901 (13 > 12)`. Fixed by extracting two new `@staticmethod` helpers (`_defer_gate`, `_impl_go_route`) mirroring the sibling `_skip_gate` extraction style already established on the class. Cross-references the `cyclomatic-complexity-noqa-suppression-planning` skill (different topic: audits accumulated `noqa` suppressions, not rebase-introduced violations).
- Extended `#### L. Test mock divergence after rebase` with a distinct variant: a test file BYTE-IDENTICAL on both sides of the rebase (never touched by conflict resolution) still broke, because an unrelated commit in the same PR changed `_handle_clean_go`'s terminal disposition elsewhere in the same source file. Documents searching sibling tests in the same class for an already-correct expected-value pattern before hand-deriving a new one.
- Added a new row to `#### C. Conflict resolution decision table` plus a new `#### C4. Doc/policy conflict as a chronology question — resolve file-wide, not per-hunk` subsection: `docs/ci/required-checks.md` had only 2 explicit conflict hunks but restated the same `strict:true`/`strict:false` policy fact ~6 times; only 2 restatements were inside conflict markers, so 4 auto-merged silently with the stale value. Resolution requires grepping the whole file for the same value/keyword and applying the chronologically-current side (tie-broken by commit `632d3ec9` and a backing regression test) consistently everywhere, not just inside markers.
- Added `#### R. Deleted file leaves a stale inventory-table row — caught only by a dedicated consistency hook`: a cleanly-auto-merged file deletion (`.github/workflows/enable-auto-merge-on-implementation-go.yml`) left an orphaned row in `.github/workflows/README.md`'s Workflow Summary table, caught only by the whole-tree `hephaestus-check-workflow-inventory` pre-commit hook.
- Added 3 new `## Failed Attempts` rows: declaring a large rebase clean on markers-plus-individual-hunks alone; resolving a doc/policy conflict hunk-by-hunk without a whole-file grep; and over-trusting a changed-files-scoped `pre-commit run` as equivalent to `--all-files` for inventory-consistency hooks.
- Added a new `## Verified On` row for HomericIntelligence/ProjectHephaestus PR #2056.
- Added new `tags:` entries (kebab-case) covering the four new patterns: `complexity-after-rebase`, `c901-from-clean-merge`, `extract-method-mirror-sibling`, `stale-test-assertion-unmodified-file`, `byte-identical-test-file`, `shared-contract-change`, `sibling-test-pattern-reuse`, `doc-policy-chronology-conflict`, `whole-file-grep`, `restated-value-consistency`, `self-contradictory-doc`, `stale-inventory-table-row`, `deleted-file-orphan-reference`, `workflow-inventory-hook`, `full-pre-commit-suite`, `whole-tree-lint`, `silent-auto-merge-defect`.
- Bumped version 1.14.0 -> 1.15.0 (MINOR — new findings/triggers extending an existing verified workflow, no breaking restructure); updated date to 2026-07-12.

### Why
The existing skill already taught two flavors of "clean auto-merge hides a defect" (§ L test-mock divergence, § K cross-PR semantic collision) but had no guidance for a THIRD flavor — two changes from the two sides of a SINGLE rebase silently combining into a complexity violation — nor for the sibling failure modes where a byte-identical test file breaks from an unrelated same-PR change, a doc conflict is really a whole-file chronology question, or a deleted file leaves a stale inventory-table row. All four were observed in one large (17-commit, 65-file) rebase session, each caught by a DIFFERENT verification mechanism (whole-tree lint, the actual test suite, whole-file grep, and a dedicated consistency hook respectively) — reinforcing that "zero conflict markers" is necessary but never sufficient evidence of a correct rebase at this scale. Future resolvers of large multi-commit rebases need the META-LESSON in § C2 and the four concrete patterns to know which heavier checks to run and why a clean per-hunk resolution can still hide a defect.

