## v1.13.0 (2026-06-30)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus issue #1429 both-added import-line conflict resolution

**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed
- Added trigger #20 and a new When-to-Use bullet for the case where two branches each APPEND a DIFFERENT `from <same-module> import <symbols>` line at the same position in the same file (a UU both-modified import-line conflict).
- Added section P documenting the verified resolution: detect with the non-mutating `git merge-tree $(git merge-base HEAD origin/main) HEAD origin/main | grep -c '<<<<<<<'` dry-run, recognize that a DIRTY PR can have a fully green CI rollup (the conflict is the sole blocker), UNION the imported symbols into ONE ruff-ordered statement (never pick `--ours`/`--theirs`, which silently drops a symbol → NameError/unused-import), then verify at RUNTIME with `python -c` importing both symbols plus `ruff check` and the targeted test class.
- Added three Failed Attempts rows: `git checkout --ours/--theirs` on a both-added import line (drops a symbol), trusting the green CI rollup as mergeable (DIRTY blocks independently), and assuming `git merge-tree` mutates the worktree (it is read-only).
- Added Results & Parameters entries: `both_added_import_line`, `conflict_dry_run`, `dirty_with_green_ci`, `runtime_import_verify`.
- Added a Verified On row for ProjectHephaestus issue #1429 (`ci_driver.py` both-added `hephaestus.constants` import) with verified-local result.
- Added tags: `import-line-conflict`, `union-imports`, `both-added-import`, `same-module-import`, `merge-tree-dry-run`, `dirty-all-green`, `runtime-import-verify`, `ruff-import-order`, `no-pick-a-side`.
- Bumped version 1.12.0 -> 1.13.0 (MINOR — new verified workflow section § P + failed attempts); updated date to 2026-06-30.

### Why
Existing coverage handled AA (both-added) FILE conflicts and a passing mention of "merge import lists" buried inside the cluster-extraction context (§ K3), but did not capture the standalone, high-frequency case of two branches each adding a DIFFERENT import of the SAME module on one line. That case is distinctive because the otherwise-safe "take main for source files" shortcut is WRONG — main's side is an INDEPENDENT addition, not a superset, so picking either side silently drops a needed symbol and breaks at import/usage time. It also reinforces that a green CI rollup does not imply mergeability and that `git merge-tree` is a safe non-mutating way to measure conflicts before and after resolution.

## v1.12.0 (2026-06-29)

**Changed by:** Inference Service PR #289 safe cleanup and Warden rebase recovery

**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed
- Added trigger #19 and a new When-to-Use bullet for Inference Service H200 Slurm PR branches where a stale/dirty local checkout must be preserved before rebase and master renamed the control lifecycle to Warden.
- Added section O documenting the verified PR #289 workflow: patch backup + backup branch + stash before reset, rebase onto `origin/master`, non-interactive `env GIT_EDITOR=true git rebase --continue`, Warden env-name resolution, targeted validation, and explicit force-with-lease.
- Added Failed Attempts rows for hard-resetting before preserving unrelated staged work, resolving Warden conflicts back to old control env names, interactive `git rebase --continue` in a non-interactive session, and passing shell scripts to Ruff.
- Added Results & Parameters entries for Inference Service trunk, dirty-checkout safeguards, Warden conflict rules, shell validation, Python validation, and explicit leases.
- Added a Verified On row for Inference Service PR #289 with verified-ci result: PR head `bbf82e799fa430f868af3d96c807e1e18a5eb15a`, GitHub `mergeStateStatus=CLEAN`, `mergeable=MERGEABLE`, no unresolved review threads, and green required checks.
- Added tags: `inference_service`, `warden`, `slurm`, `h200`, `dirty-local-checkout`, `staged-work-backup`, `explicit-force-lease`, `uv-verify`, `ruff-shell-split`.
- Bumped version 1.11.0 -> 1.12.0 (MINOR — new verified workflow section + failed attempts); updated date to 2026-06-29.

### Why
Inference Service PR #289 combined three hazards that the existing generic rebase skill did not capture together: unrelated local staged work in a stale PR checkout, a branch rebase across the control-to-Warden lifecycle rename, and a force-push to a shared PR branch. The safe workflow required preserving local work through three independent recovery paths before reset, resolving conflicts by keeping Warden env names while preserving nested `srun --mem=0`, validating with the repo's targeted `uv`, Ruff, shell, and manifest checks, and force-pushing only with a lease pinned to the observed old remote SHA.

