    | ProjectOdyssey | 2026-06-19, PR #5500 (`5451-auto-impl` branch): main had already merged the same shampoo.mojo, lion.mojo, and test_optimizers.mojo files the feature branch was implementing, causing AA conflicts across 3 commits. Key diagnostic: AA-conflicted files had NO `<<<<<<<` markers — file showed one side's content only. Resolution: `git show HEAD:<path>` / `git show REBASE_HEAD:<path>` to read both sides, took main's version for source files + cherry-picked unique wrapper functions from feature branch, union of test cases for test file. One commit was upstream-equivalent after resolution and needed `git rebase --skip`. Branch force-pushed with `--force-with-lease` and PR updated. | verified-local |
    | ProjectHephaestus | 2026-06-26, 5-PR same-file refactor cluster (issues #1383/#1384/#1381/#1385/#1392, PRs #1613/#1615/#1612/#1616/#1621 — all merged): every PR edited `address_review.py`; 4 also touched `_review_utils.py` + `ci_driver.py`. The automation loop dispatched them in parallel with no file-overlap serialization, so only the first merged and the other 4 went CONFLICTING/DIRTY; an operator `state:skip` then stranded them. Unblocked by serializing into a smallest-diff-first rebase chain: each branch rebased onto trunk only AFTER the prior PR merged (conflicts shrank as extractions accumulated upstream), every conflict union-resolved (both helpers kept in `_review_utils.py`; each duplicated method made a thin delegate in the consumers; import lists merged and now-unused imports like `add_max_workers_arg` dropped via ruff), commits re-signed with `git rebase --exec "git commit --amend --no-edit -s -S" origin/main` for DCO+GPG. Two members carried `state:implementation-no-go` and earned `state:implementation-go` via `hephaestus-implement-issues` rather than a forced label flip. All 5 merged. | verified-ci |
    | ProjectHephaestus | 2026-06-27, PR #1633 (issue #1405): Rebased autoimpl-generated PR onto origin/main; git conflicts in `hephaestus/github/pr_merge.py` and `tidy.py` resolved cleanly (no markers). Post-rebase tests failed with mock signature mismatches: test mocks expected PR's refactored code (`run_subprocess` calls) but rebase brought origin/main's pre-refactor implementation (`subprocess.check_output` calls). TRIGGER #18 / § L scenario: textual conflict resolved but semantic divergence hidden until test-run. FIX: regenerated test mocks to match ACTUAL current implementation (not PR's expected changes). Changed subprocess mocking target from `subprocess.check_output` back to `run_subprocess`; updated test function signatures to match current module. Also fixed implementation bug: `local_branch_exists()` needed to use `run_subprocess` to match test expectations of current code. verified-ci: all 335 github tests pass, pre-commit clean. | verified-ci |
    | ProjectHephaestus | 2026-06-27, PR #1657 (Option-A timeout rebase) — STALE MERGE-BASE: two Opus agents each reported "rebased onto origin/main, force-pushed", but `git merge-base origin/main origin/<branch>` stayed at the stale base (29 commits behind) and the branch never contained `load_state_file` (a known main-only symbol from a merged sibling). Root cause: a later force-push from a worktree built on the OLD branch tip silently reset the base. Lesson: after any claimed rebase, verify `git merge-base origin/main HEAD == origin/main` (re-fetch first) AND grep the pushed branch for a known main-only symbol; create the rebase worktree from the CURRENT `origin/<branch>` and re-verify the remote merge-base after pushing (§ M). | verified-ci |
    | ProjectHephaestus | 2026-06-27, PR #1657 (Option-A timeout rebase) — HALF-APPLIED MULTI-LAYER REFACTOR: a per-phase-timeout restore (300/1800/600 over a flat 7200) was resolved correctly in `models.py` (`AGENT_PLAN_TIMEOUT=300`, `AGENT_IMPL_TIMEOUT=1800`) but every `*_claude_timeout()` helper in `claude_timeouts.py` still returned the flat `DEFAULT_AGENT_TIMEOUT=7200`, and `constants.py`'s `AGENT_*` constants + `read_timeout_env` were deleted. Passed a `models.py` spot-check; caught only by CI's `assert 300 == 7200` (test `test_uses_central_learn_timeout`). Fix: take main's constants/helpers/tests wholesale (`git show origin/main:<file> > <file>`), re-add only the PR's new CLI DEFAULT_ constant, assert the actual function returns (`planner_claude_timeout()==300`), run the contract test (§ N). | verified-ci |
````

---

## v1.11.0 (2026-06-27)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus #1657 Option-A timeout rebase

**Verification:** verified-ci

**What changed:** Added TWO new failure modes discovered while rebasing
ProjectHephaestus PR #1657 (Option-A per-phase timeout restore):

- **Failure mode A — rebase reported success but the branch was NEVER re-parented
  (stale merge-base).** Two Opus agents each claimed to rebase onto current main and
  force-push, but `git merge-base origin/main origin/<branch>` stayed at the stale base
  (29 commits behind) and the branch never contained a known main-only symbol
  (`load_state_file`) from a merged sibling. Root cause: the rebase ran from/onto a stale
  ref, or a later force-push from a SECOND worktree built off the OLD branch tip silently
  reset the base. Added new **Section M** ("Rebase reported success but the branch was
  NEVER re-parented (stale merge-base)") with the MANDATORY post-rebase verification
  contract: re-fetch, then `git merge-base origin/main HEAD == git rev-parse origin/main`
  (and the same against `origin/<branch>` to catch a wrong-base force-push) AND grep the
  pushed branch for a known main-only symbol (`git show origin/<branch>:<file> | grep -c
  <symbol>` > 0). Prevention: always create the rebase worktree from the CURRENT
  `origin/<branch>` and re-verify the remote merge-base after pushing.

- **Failure mode B — half-applied multi-layer refactor rebase (options-object defaults
  fixed but the helper FUNCTIONS still flattened).** A per-phase-timeout restore
  (300/1800/600 over a flat 7200) was resolved correctly in `models.py`
  (`AGENT_PLAN_TIMEOUT=300`, `AGENT_IMPL_TIMEOUT=1800`) but every `*_claude_timeout()`
  helper in `claude_timeouts.py` still returned the flat `DEFAULT_AGENT_TIMEOUT=7200`, and
  `constants.py`'s `AGENT_*` constants + `read_timeout_env` were DELETED. The regression
  passed a `models.py` spot-check and was caught ONLY by CI's `assert 300 == 7200` (test
  `test_uses_central_learn_timeout`). Added new **Section N** ("Half-applied multi-layer
  refactor rebase") with the correct resolution: for a "restore main's values" conflict
  take main's constants/helpers/tests files WHOLESALE (`git show origin/main:<file> >
  <file>`), then re-add ONLY the PR's genuinely-new additions (e.g. a new CLI `DEFAULT_`
  constant); add explicit per-value assertions (`assert planner_claude_timeout()==300`);
  run the contract test; and READ the CI `assert 300 == 7200` output to pinpoint the
  still-flattened layer.

- Added two new **When to Use** triggers (one per failure mode) plus matching
  common-trigger phrases ("agent said it rebased but merge-base is stale", "branch is N
  commits behind after a claimed rebase", "rebased timeout PR but functions still return
  the flat value", "assert 300 == 7200 after rebase").
- Added two new **Failed Attempts** rows: (A) trusting a rebase agent's "rebased and
  force-pushed" self-report when the merge-base stayed stale; (B) resolving a multi-layer
  timeout refactor by fixing only `models.py` while the helper functions stayed flattened.
- Added two **Verified On** rows for ProjectHephaestus PR #1657 (stale-merge-base and
  half-applied-multi-layer cases).
- Added tags: `rebase-not-reparented`, `stale-merge-base`, `merge-base-verification`,
  `main-only-symbol-check`, `false-rebase-success`, `half-applied-refactor`,
  `per-phase-timeout-regression`, `multi-layer-refactor`, `options-object-vs-helpers`,
  `value-regression`.
- Bumped version 1.10.0 → 1.11.0 (MINOR — new failed attempts + workflow sections);
  updated date to 2026-06-27.

**Why:** The skill already covered textual conflict resolution and post-rebase test-mock
divergence (§ L), but had no guidance for two distinct ways a rebase can SILENTLY not do
what a self-report claims. Failure mode A is a process failure: a "success" report is not
evidence the branch re-parented — only the merge-base equality plus a main-only-symbol grep
is. Failure mode B is a resolution-completeness failure: when a refactor spans several
layers (constants + helper functions + options-object defaults + tests), fixing the most
visible layer while leaving the parallel layers flattened produces a regression that passes
spot-checks but fails CI. Both wasted multiple CI rounds on #1657 before being root-caused
to the merge-base and the actual `assert 300 == 7200` test output respectively.

**Previous v1.10.0 state (snapshot):** v1.10.0 carried the skill through trigger #18 / § L
("Test mock divergence after rebase — regenerate mocks against actual implementation",
ProjectHephaestus PR #1633 / issue #1405): rebase completes with no conflict markers but
tests fail on mock signature mismatches because the rebase brought in origin/main's
different implementation; fix is to regenerate the test mocks against the ACTUAL current
code, never to "fix" the code to match stale test expectations. The full v1.10.0 file
(frontmatter through § L, the Failed Attempts table up to the `state:skip` cluster row, and
the Verified On table through the #1633 row) is preserved in git history at the commit
prior to this amendment.

## v1.9.0 (2026-06-26)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus 5-PR same-file refactor cluster #1383/1384/1381/1385/1392
(PRs #1613/#1615/#1612/#1616/#1621 — all merged). Five sibling refactor PRs all edited
`address_review.py`; four also touched `_review_utils.py` + `ci_driver.py`. The automation loop ran
them in parallel with no file-overlap serialization, so only the first merged and the rest went
CONFLICTING/DIRTY; an operator `state:skip` then permanently stranded them.

**Verification:** verified-ci — all five PRs merged after serializing into a smallest-first rebase
chain with union-resolved extractions and re-signed (DCO+GPG) commits.

**What changed:**

- Added **trigger (17)** to frontmatter `description`: a CLUSTER of sibling refactor PRs all edit the
  SAME shared files and were run in parallel so all but one are CONFLICTING/DIRTY (and possibly
  hand-braked with `state:skip`) — land them as a SEQUENTIAL rebase chain SMALLEST-DIFF-FIRST,
  rebasing each onto trunk only AFTER the prior merges, union-resolving each refactor's extractions
  into thin delegates (merge import lists, drop now-unused imports via lint), then re-sign with
  `git rebase --exec '...-s -S' origin/main` for DCO+GPG.
- Added a new `When to Use` bullet describing the same-file refactor cluster and pointing to § K3;
  notes it complements trigger #15/§ K2 (resolving ONE add/add conflict) by ordering N
  mutually-conflicting refactors.
- Added **Section K3** ("Cluster of same-file refactor PRs → sequential smallest-first rebase chain")
  documenting the five-step orchestration: (1) order smallest-diff-first so conflicts shrink as the
  chain progresses, with a `gh pr view` ranking snippet; (2) union-resolve extractions — keep both
  helpers in the shared module, make each duplicated method a thin delegate, merge import lists, drop
  now-unused imports via ruff; (3) rebase each branch onto `origin/main` ONLY after the prior PR
  merges; (4) re-sign with the copy-paste `git rebase --exec "git commit --amend --no-edit -s -S"
  origin/main` command for DCO + GPG; (5) earn `state:implementation-go` via
  `hephaestus-implement-issues` rather than force-flipping `state:implementation-no-go`.
- Added a **Failed Attempts** row: tried to rebase/land all cluster PRs in parallel (as the loop did)
  — only the first merged; the other 4 went CONFLICTING and `state:skip` stranded them; lesson:
  serialize a same-file refactor cluster into a smallest-first rebase chain because the loop's
  parallel dispatch has no file-overlap awareness.
- Added tags: `same-file-cluster`, `sequential-rebase-chain`, `smallest-first`, `thin-delegate`,
  `union-resolution`, `dco-signoff`, `state-skip-stranded`.
- Added a **Verified On** row: ProjectHephaestus 2026-06-26 5-PR cluster, all merged.
- Bumped version 1.8.0 → 1.9.0; updated date to 2026-06-26.

**Why:** The skill already covered resolving ONE add/add conflict between two parallel extractions
(trigger #15 / § K2), but had no guidance for the broader operational problem of an entire CLUSTER of
N refactor PRs that all edit the same shared files and were dispatched in parallel with no
file-overlap awareness. Without serialization only the first merges and the rest go CONFLICTING; an
operator `state:skip` then strands them indefinitely. § K3 supplies the missing orchestration:
smallest-diff-first sequencing (so conflicts shrink), union-into-thin-delegates resolution,
rebase-only-after-prior-merges, DCO+GPG re-signing, and earning (not forcing) the implementation-go
label.

**Previous v1.8.0 description line (snapshot):**

> "Use when: (1) a PR branch is CONFLICTING or DIRTY after main advances and needs rebasing … (15)
> two parallel cluster-extraction PRs both create the same new module file and the rebase produces an
> add/add conflict on BOTH the source module AND its test file — main's source is authoritative, test
> files must be semantically merged … (16) a rebase hits AA (both-added) conflicts on new files — the
> conflicted file shows NO `<<<<<<<` markers and contains only one side's content; you must use git
> show HEAD:<path> and git show REBASE_HEAD:<path> to read both versions before resolving"

## v1.8.0 (2026-06-19)

**Changed by:** ProjectOdyssey PR #5500 (`5451-auto-impl` branch) — AA (both-added) conflicts on
shampoo.mojo, lion.mojo, and test_optimizers.mojo when main had already merged the same new files
the feature branch was adding.

**Verification:** verified-local — rebase completed successfully, branch force-pushed with
`--force-with-lease`, PR updated.

**What changed:**

- Added **trigger (16)** to frontmatter `description`: a rebase hits AA (both-added) conflicts on
  new files — the conflicted file shows NO `<<<<<<<` markers and contains only one side's content;
  must use `git show HEAD:<path>` and `git show REBASE_HEAD:<path>` to read both versions.
- Added new `When to Use` bullet: AA (both-added) conflicts with no markers — `git status`
  left-column `AA` vs `UU` distinction, and how to read both sides.
- Added **Section C3** ("AA vs UU conflict detection — 'no markers' diagnostic") covering: reading
  `git status` left-column codes (AA vs UU vs DD/UD/DU), why AA files have no `<<<<<<<` markers,
  how to read both sides with `git show HEAD:<path>` / `git show REBASE_HEAD:<path>`, resolution
  options (take main, take branch, manual merge), the "main already merged your feature" pattern,
  and when to use `git rebase --skip` vs `--continue` after AA resolution.
- Added **3 Failed Attempts** rows: (1) searching for `<<<<<<<` markers in an AA conflict (they
  don't exist — check `git status` codes first); (2) calling `git rebase --continue` before all
  AA-conflicted files were staged; (3) calling `git rebase --continue` on a commit whose content
  was already on main (needed `--skip` instead).
- Added tags: `aa-conflict`, `uu-conflict`, `both-added`, `git-status-codes`, `no-markers`.
- Added a **Verified On** row: ProjectOdyssey PR #5500, 2026-06-19 — AA conflicts on 3 new files
  across 3 commits; resolved by `git show HEAD/<REBASE_HEAD>:<path>` inspection + taking main's
  source + union of tests; one commit needed `--skip`.

**Why:** The existing skill covered add/add conflict resolution in sections C (decision table) and
K2 (cluster-extraction), but never documented the critical diagnostic fact that **AA conflicts have
NO `<<<<<<<` markers**. An agent opening an AA-conflicted file and seeing no markers may falsely
conclude the conflict was already resolved or search for markers that don't exist, wasting time.
The explicit `git status` left-column code guide (AA vs UU) and the `git show HEAD/<REBASE_HEAD>`
read pattern for AA files are the gap-filling additions.

## v1.7.0 (2026-06-15)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus issue #1357 (CIDriver decomposition) — CC Safety Net blocks `git checkout --theirs` and `git restore --source=REBASE_HEAD` during rebase conflict resolution

**Verification:** verified-local — cat-through-tmp pattern executed successfully during rebase conflict resolution; files resolved correctly and commits proceeded.

**What changed:**

- Added **cat-through-tmp alternative** to Quick Reference section 5 (Safety-Net-safe conflict resolution): `git show REBASE_HEAD:<path> > /tmp/X && cat /tmp/X > <dest> && git add <dest>` as an explicit alternative for when you want a named-ref version rather than a stage-number version.
- Expanded **Section I** (Safety Net constraints) with a dedicated "Cat-through-tmp pattern" subsection explaining the mechanism: Safety Net pattern-matches on `git checkout <file-args>` and `git restore --source=<ref>` by command name; `git show <ref>:<path>` is read-only and the `cat /tmp/X > <dest>` write step is a pure shell operation that Safety Net does not intercept.
- Added a **Failed Attempts** row: `git checkout --theirs <file>` blocked ("may overwrite files") and `git restore --source=REBASE_HEAD -- <file>` blocked ("discards uncommitted changes") during rebase conflict resolution in a Safety-Net-protected environment; workaround is `git show REBASE_HEAD:<path> > /tmp/X && cat /tmp/X > <dest> && git add <dest>`.

**Why:** The existing skill documented `git show :2:/:3:` stage-number writes for conflict take but did not document the `git show <ref>:<path> > /tmp/X && cat` pattern. The stage-number approach requires an active conflict (unmerged paths in index), while the cat-through-tmp approach works whenever you want any specific ref's version of a file and `git checkout`/`git restore` are blocked — including mid-rebase when both commands are blocked by the Safety Net.

## v1.5.0 (2026-06-14)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus 2026-06-14 serial merge-train (~12 PRs) — broken-main semantic-collision diagnosis

**Verification:** verified-local — the new v1.5.0 material was observed live this session driving a serial merge-train to completion; the fix PR (#1340 / issue #1339) had NOT yet merged at capture, so the runtime break and its 1-line-mock fix are verified-local. The skill remains verified-ci overall (prior material).

**What changed:**

- Added **trigger (14)** to frontmatter `description`: multiple rebased PRs — including ones unrelated to the failing test — all fail the SAME test after merging onto main; suspect a broken main from a SEMANTIC collision between two independently-merged PRs that never textually conflict (e.g. a return-tuple arity change + a stale test mock); prove it by running the failing test against bare `origin/main`, and fix main first.
- Added a **When to Use** bullet for the broken-main-from-semantic-collision scenario (distinct from all textual-conflict cases — the rebase is clean, only a test run catches the inconsistency).
- Added **Section K** ("Broken main from a semantic collision between two independently-merged PRs") covering: the symptom (same test fails across multiple unrelated rebased PRs), the root cause (two PRs each green alone, inconsistent in union at runtime, no conflict markers), the concrete ProjectHephaestus case (#1336 9-tuple return vs #1337 stale 7-tuple mock → `ValueError: not enough values to unpack (expected 9, got 7)` at `_review_phase.py:635`), and the 6-step diagnosis procedure (get exact failing test from `gh run view --log-failed`; same test on multiple unrelated PRs ⇒ suspect main; PROVE main red by running the test against bare `origin/main` in a clean worktree; locate the function's real return arity + the stale mock; FIX MAIN FIRST in one small PR; re-green trailing PRs by re-running CI).
- **Strengthened pre-flight** (Quick Reference #0 and Detailed Steps A.2): main can go RED *after* the train starts as siblings merge — RE-CHECK main is green before EACH rebase wave; treat two PRs that touch the same function-and-its-test (a return-tuple/arity/signature change + a mock of that function) as a latent collision even though they will never textually conflict.
- Added **2 Failed Attempts** rows: (1) assuming a rebased PR's red CI is the PR's fault when the same test fails across multiple unrelated PRs (it was main, from the 9-tuple-vs-7-tuple-mock collision) → run the test against bare `origin/main` to prove it, fix main first; (2) trying to fix the broken test inside each trailing PR (the breakage is shared) → land ONE main-fix PR, then re-green the queue.
- Added a **Verified On** row: ProjectHephaestus 2026-06-14 merge-train — 8/12 merged, trailing 4 red on `test_review_loop_resolves_conflict_before_first_review`; root-caused to #1336+#1337 independent-merge collision; fixed via 1-line mock PR (#1340 / issue #1339).
- Added tags: `semantic-collision`, `broken-main`, `tuple-arity`, `stale-mock`, `merge-train-cascade`.

**Why:** Every prior class in this skill is a TEXTUAL conflict surfaced by rebase/merge. This is the first documented class with NO conflict markers: two PRs that never touch overlapping lines (a function's return-tuple arity change in one, a stale mock of that function in another) each pass their own CI, but their UNION on main fails at runtime. It is invisible to conflict resolution and only a test run catches it. The diagnostic tell — the SAME test failing across MULTIPLE unrelated rebased PRs — and the discipline of proving main is red against `origin/main` before touching any PR, plus fixing main ONCE rather than per-PR, are the additions.

